<br>
the main problem with trying to think of something original is that everything has been done befor. you just have to choose one that hasnt been done correctly or recently enough for most people to remember it. Not to say that you should copy anything, but there is a good chance that even if you think of something independantly, it will resemble some movie or comic that already exists. Thats okay, we arnt in the reneissance anymore where everything is new, so its unavoidable.<br>
<br>
i usually start with characters, because i like personality studies more than just straight action. I try to think of a character who has more problems than good things. if there is one character that is annoying to read about it is perfect people, like James Bond in the movies or for instance Howard Roark in Ayn Rand's Fountainhead. Roark is almost inhuman in his perfect obediance to his principals and his almost total lack of character flaws. Rand writes the book extremly well, but those kinds of characters are too unrelateable. I prefer a character who has to struggle morally every day, and in the end doesn't get everything they wished for. Regardless of what genra you are writing about, you should try to get inside your characters instead of using cookie cutter steriotypes to populate your story. i'd prefer to read about a character that fails a lot; then when he does succeed, it makes it that much more rewarding.<br>
<br>
